The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. title: Want To Buy:  Need Decent Gunsmith
postcontent:
So I fired some over loaded reloads through my Zastava M77.  A spent cartridge got stuck and when I attempted to hammer the bolt open it ripped off the base of the cartridge leaving a brass tube severely fused to the chamber with nothing to grip on and no way to use a rod to punch it out. I ended up using a little screwdriver and a hammer to bend a part of the shell up enough to get a rod on.  I got the shell out but in the processes I burred up the chamber.  The rifle still fires as is but it jams more than it did, especially with steel cased rounds.  I need to find somebody to smooth out the burrs if possible. I understand there will still be gouges but I think the gun will work better without sharp metal scratching against the rounds as they go in and out. 

The pictures are a little hard to see but what they show are the burrs in the chamber and how the shells look coming out.  If you think you can fix this please email me with a little about your experience and approximate cost, turnover time, and area of city.  Would prefer to stick with Sac area. Keep in mind this is an AK style rifle and it would not be easy to get any kind of tool into the chamber in a straight shot.  Please only principles contact me, I don't need recommendations I can use google and yelp.  Thanks for reading.

title: For Trade:  Stoeger Cougar Compact
postcontent:
I have a Stoeger Cougar compact I'm interested in trading.

If you aren't familiar with the Cougar design it is the precursor to the Beretta PX4 and uses a rotating barrel action to improve accuracy and lower recoil.  Identical to the Beretta Cougar aside from the name on the slide; Beretta transferred the tooling and manufacturing equipment to Stoeger, Stoeger being a subdivision of Benelli, which is in turn owned by Beretta.  Has the same manual of arms as a Beretta 92/M9, so its a great choice if you're looking for a more compact version for carry.

Has some light holster wear from being carried but overall is in good shape, bought new about two months ago and only has about 200 rounds through it.  Will come with two 13 round magazines. Depending on what you have I can also include an extra 15 round magazine (modified Beretta 92 mag) and I have a fair amount of 9mm ammo.

Primarily looking for a subcompact 9mm striker fired pistol in trade, really looking for a Ruger SR9c or LC9s (must be the striker fired LC9s, not interested in the standard LC9).
